ce.\na\nThe Times proceeds to discuss\nthe controversy in the following man\nner:\n\"But what becomes of the senatorial\nprivilege! Cannot a man from Tdaho\nbe permitted to keep his record straight\nwith his constituents, nnd to sec to it\nthat his political fences are in prime or\ndert Senator Borah is ambitious, and\nthe necessity of winning and holding\nthe confidence of the people lies heavy\nupon him. He must not be so radical\nas to alarm the Republicans, nor yet so\nreactionary as to scare away the Pro\ngressives.\n\"So why shouldn't he, as Mr. Per\nkins puts it, make a pussyfooted speech\nat a New York banquet and sail into\nbig business hot and heavy in Ohio two\nweeks later \u00ce Tf Mr. Perkins was out\nfor the nomination in 1916 he would nn\nderstand these things better.\n\"The use the politicians make of the\ncorporations and business interests for\ntheir private ends has its serious side,\nhowever. Mr. Perkins assumes from\nSenator Borah 's letter that he is in\nfavor of breaking up the Steel corpora\ntion. We do not know how the Idaho\nsenator stands upon that question, but\ncertainly there are many senators and\nmany congressmen who would, with\ngreat pleasure, read a dissolution decree\nwith respect to that concern. Yet, as\nMr. Perkins points out, the consequenc\nes of dissolution would fall very heavi\nly upon the large percentage of Steel\ncorporation 's employees who are own\ners of its shares. \"In the month of\nJanuary just passed,'' says Mr. Perkins,\n\"42,393 employes subscribed as sepn\nrate individuals for an aggregate of\nover 80,000 shares of stork in that com\npany. The establishment nnd suc\ncessful dplelopment of this plan for\ngiving thp men in the mills a share of\nthe profit is very largely thp work of\nMr. Perkins, as he reminds Senator\nBorah. Tt may be doubted whether any\nsenator or congressman with an ovp\nchiefly to his own political interests\ntakes thought about the harm he may\nbe doing\u2014not to the capitalists\u2014but to\nthe wage earners who are measureably\ndependent for a comfortable living up\non the activity of business nnd the gen\neral prosperity of the country.\nThen it throws in the following by\n\"Mr. J. J. Hill\n\nway of good measure:\nsaid the other day that this is a big\ncountry and it takes a good many men\nto hold it down. There are men in\nWashington, many men, who are doing\ntheir best to hold it down, who are\nto the extent of their abilities and their\nrecklessness obstructing the return of\nprosperity. The harm inflicted upon\nthe working class, upon the common\npeople, by the agitators and demago\ngues of polities is and has been im\nmeasurably greater than any injury due\nto the extortions of the trusts\nSo Senator Borah's next move may\nnot only be in the direetion of Per\nkins, hnt in the direction of the Times.\nHis reply will be awaited with in\nterest, containing as it will, of course,\nfacts and figures to sustain his sweep\ning charges against Perkins, and a per\norational burst anent his classification\nby the Times as a demagogue and (O\nLord!) a pussyfoot and trimmer!\nPerkins and the Times have given\nSenator Borah a golden opportunity.\nImagine the Congressional Record\nDIXIE\n(From the Enterprise.)\nW. N. Robinson and Elmer Wadling\nthis week at Judge Hazilitt's ranch\non Salmon river.\nElmer Wadling and Leslie Powelson\nwent to Big Creek last week, reported\nfour feet of snow in that vicinity.\nJudge Hazlitt went to Salmon river\nto make preparartions for planting gar\nden but finding the garden still covered\nwith snow he returned to Dixie Mon\nday.\nare\nAllan Stonbreaker and Fred Great\nreturned from Chamberlain Basin\nores\nprinted in colors, principally red, and\nyou have some idea of what may be\n\u2014Cincinnati Euquirer.\nthere is a man in our town\ncoming.\nPASS IT ALONG.\non\nthe\nThe re is a man\nn our town\nof\nAnd he is full of\nlie has a\nprunes;\nrusty phonograph\nAnd never chauges tunes.\nas\nOur goat for sure he got;\nHe dumps all sorts of rubbish\nHis vacant corner lot.\nou\nAllentown Democrat.\nthere is u man in our town\nWho helps mosquitoes breed;\nHe owns a world of vacant lots,\nAnd never cuts a weed.\n\u2014Houston Post,\nof\nThere is a\nWho's even worse than that;\nHe 's taching tango dancing\nThe floor above our flat.\nman in our town\nOil\n\u2014Chicago Record-Herald.\nThere is a man in our town\u2014\nA pest you probably know\u2014\nNo matter what the days brings forth,\nHe says I told you so.''\na\n\u2014Louisville Herald.\nThere is a man in our town,\nFor hot Avernus bound;\nEach night he ties in his back yard\nHis cussed, howling hound.\nSau Francisco Chronicle.\nThere is a man in our town,\nWho sits behind your seat;\nAnd everything the actors say,\nHe thinks he must repeat.\n\u2014Goodwiu'H Weekly.\nThere is a man in our town\nWho for closeuess, can't be boat\nlie does his talking through his\nThat he may save his teeth.\nit\nnose\n\u2014Troy Weekly News\nThere is a man in our town\nWho's got him beat a block;\nWhenever he goes out visiting\nHe always stops the dock.\n\u2014The Lapwai Messenger.\nThere is a man in our town\nSo lazy, close, aud jay\nHe never mends his bloomin' walk\nOr clears it dirt away.\n\u2014'Moscow Star-Mirror.\nThere is a man in our town\nAnd you know who we mean\nHe can write a check in figures nine\nBut he never spends a bean.\nBASE BALL BUG CHIRPS MERRY\nLAY TO BECKONING CALL OF\nSPRING'S FIRST SUNNY DAYS.\n1\n(Continued from page 1.)\nat home isn't the basic principle upon\nwhich this new thought finds a footing.\nIt's the belief, almost universally ex\npressed, that a well-selected team of\nplayers who reside in or near Orange\nville could, under the proper manage\nment and guidance, be shaped into a\nwinning organization. Ball teams which\nhave represented Grangeville in the\npast and which have been made up of\nmore or less imported players have done\nwell enough and there is certainly noth\ning hut praise due to all who have been\nconnected with the teams, or the\nmanagement of the teams, in years\n'adily\ngone by. However, if can be ri\nrecalled that the home boys, even in\ncompetition with the imported phenoms,\nhave never fallen down so terribly or\nfailed in the pinches.\nIn the past, with costly ouside play\ners on the team, we have lost and won.\nIt will probably be the same when we\nuse a strictly local talent team.\nPitching Department Strong.\nOne thing is certain; Grangeville ap\npears to be well fortified in the box\nthis year. With Janaseo, a southpaw\nwho hails from Minnesota and who\nbrings a record of shutouts and vic\ntories as long as his arm, and Tngrnm,\nwho like wine improves with age, we\nshould not shed iscb-ga-bibble tears\nabout the twirling staff. Mr. Janaseo 1 b\nthe new bookkeeper at the Grangeville\nSavings Trust Company tank. In\ngram is in line for the best base ball\nyear of his life and will probably alter\nnate between the pitcher's box and\nsecond base. Janaseo, too, handles an\ninfield position when he isn't hurling\nstrikes and balls.\nFor backstop there's Miller, a new\nplayer, and Floyd Manning, who was a\nstar catcher in his days at high School\nand who according to many of the fans,\nis first class material for a dependable\nbattery mate.\nInfielders we have in abundance.\nLook over the list: Abrahamson whose\nproficiency at first or second is well\nknown to local followers of the game;\ni t\nthis week. They reported a foot of\nsnow in the basin, the hill sides bare\nand the grass green.\nMr. Ludwig and Jas. Moore came up\nfrom Salmon river this week\nLeslie Powelson is doing some devel\nopment work on the Skylark.\nFred Silgee, of Salmon River, spent\na few days in Dixie, last week\nJudge Hazilett is doing development\nwork on the Monadnosck north of town.\nGeorge Trader has gone to the Mas\ncot to dismantle his mill and bring it\nto Dixie.\nT\nIngram, who can be used anywhere\ni the left hand aide of the diamond wheu\nhe isn't pitching; Homer McDonald,\none of the home boys who has develop\ned rapidly the past few years and who\nis ready to shine in fast company; Kd\ntfnr Brandon, who is coaching the high\nschool track team and is williug to play\nalmost anywhere in the infield or in the\nouter gardens; both Snyder and Miller\nwho comprise the local harness manu\nfacturing firm of that name, are both\nplayers who enjoy the national game\nand\non\nare williug to get out and help\nOrangeville win a pennant.\nOthers who are in the same frame of\nmind are Charles Branscoinbe, who led\nthe North Idaho league with the stick\nlust year, batting .415; \"Pap\" Jarvis,\n\"ho played in the Three-1 league when\nthat organization had ouly two eyes;\nHenry Munro, another young fellow\nwho gives promise; Hub Wood, Wayue\nArnold, Geo. Bowman and a number of\nothers who haven't been in action for\nseveral years but who will bust a gallus\ntryin' to make the team this\nyear.\nLooks Like Fast Team.\nSummed up, we have a rttling good\nbattery made up of men who can play\nother positions in case of a shift; a\nfast, sure infield with two well known\nplayers to help develop a couple of most\npromising younger players; and we\nselect an outfield headed by a remark\nably sensational youngster and\nwho knows the game from Pop\nAnson 's day to the present. Altogeth\nit compares very favorably with lineuj\nwhich have defended the town's honor\non the diamond in the past and, what\nis more gratifying, it's a strictly home\ntalent hunch\u2014one that the busi\nmen and fans alike can support to the\nlimit. And they will.\ncan\nan \"old\nhead'\nor\n)S\nness\n\n<S>\nLOCAL AND PERSONAL\n\nMoney to loan, M. L. Ayers.\n41tf\nStoves lined and repaired at Chester\nAronld's.\n19-tf\nBefore the fire see A. F. Parker for\nfire insurance.\nFor Sale\u2014Farm lands\nproperty. Geo. M. Reed.\n15tf\nand city\n87-tf\nIron with electricity at 5 cents per\nhours. Orangeville Electric Light\nPower Co.\n3-tf\nEnglish baby buggy for sale. Good\nas new. Address Pox 368, or inquire at\nthis office.\nHot point electric iron, guaranteed 10\nyears, $3.50 Grangeville Electric Light\nPower Co.\nFor trade\u2014Will trade good house and\nlot for good young horses. Address Box\n462, Grangeville, Idaho.\n295% Acres. No. 1 wheat land. All\ncultivated. 8-rooin, house, fine well\nWindmill, barn etc. \\Vill sell on small\n1 payment, long time, low interest plan.\nWould consider some trade.\n41 tf\n35tf\n3-tf\n42-tf\nil Rhoades was taken to Cotton\n0< Hiis morning where an operation\n,or a I'pendicitis will probably be per\nformed upon him tomorrow. He came\nout from Pollock the first of the week\nWalter Ilickerson.\nand was accompanied to Cottonwood to\nday by Fet Rhoades and I)r. Turner of\nthat place.\nII. R. Newman was up from White\nbird on business a few days the first of\nthe week. He says that the farmers in\nthat country are plowing and going\nahead with spring work with fine pros\npects. Some excellent catches of trout\nfrom Whitebird creek have been re\nported, he says.\nDave Stansbury, Tom Atwood and\nJoe Roakey came over from the Wi\nnona section Monday to attend the\nmeeting of school trustees of Idaho\ncounty held here Tuesday. Dave says\nBpring has sure arrived in the reserva\ntion country, many farmers are now\nbusy plowing and some few have al\nready put in their spring grain.\nLocal Odd Fellows to the number of\nabout 20 are still talking about the\ngood times enjoyed at Fenn last Satur\nday night when the Fenn lodge took in\na class of seven candidates. A banquet\nwas served by the ladies of the two\nCamas Social clubs which, the locals\nsay, was without doubt the peer of all\nfeeds, past and present, in the history\nof such affairs.\nR. A. Lewis, the well driller, has just\ncompleted a 450 foot well on the ranch\nof Mrs. Anna Michlmon of the Winona\nsection. While some depth had to be\nattained before a suitable supply of\nwater was encountered a good flow was\nstruck at 450 feet and raised to within\n250 feet of the top. Lewis stateB this\nmakes forty-six wells he has drilled on\nthe prairie and has never yet failed to\nget ample supply of water.\nThe funniest of all farce comedies,\nOle Olson in Spiritland, will be pre\nsented at the opera house Thursday\nnight. March 19th, by Carl M. Dalton\nand his talented company of entertain\ners. While the play is an old one, it\nalways pleases, and this season it has\nbeen entirely rewritten and a large num\nber of feature specialties added, in\ncluding Bob and Ada Davis, known as\nthe whirlwind dancers, who sing and\ndance all the latest and best ragtime\ncompositions.\ni t\nStove\u00ab lined and repaired at Cheater\nArnold 'e.\n19-tf\nIf It's\n7 runf^s or\nSuitcases\nCome to\nSasenbery's\nWe have just wlmt you want\nin this lino\nCome In and Look Over Our\nSincerity Clothes\nHats, Cups, Shoes, Shirts, Gent's Furnishings, Underwear, etc., in\nstandard, recognized makes at low prloea.\nSasenbery's\n[\u2022TO\n[\u2022ra\nMost liberal reductions\non shoes and men's and\nboys' clothing\nI\nfi\nFarmers' Store\nE. J. BRISCOE, Mgr.\nBtE zr\u2014\n[\u2022ra\nYou Have a Suit\nCOMING\nThe men who purchase here have no clothes problems to solve.\nWe've solved them for you. When you put on one of our LAMM\nCOMPANY'S Made-to-Measure Suits you can feel absolutely certain\nthat It Is correct in style and of the very highest quality. You'll find\nour store service commendable, too\u2014and that alone counts for a lot\nwith most men.\nDrop In and see our new samples for both Ladles' and Gentle\nmen's Suits.\nRICHARDS'\nThe Old Reliable Tailor\nPressing, Cleaning and Altering Promtly Done.\nLadies, It Will Pay You\nto Wait\nAnd see our line of Spring Suits, Coats,\nSkirts, Waists, Dresses, Hats, Embroider\nies, Fine Laces for Corset Covers, also Chil\ndren's Hats and Dresses, Boys' Wash\nSuits.\nTHE FAIR STORE\nRemember we sell them as cheap as you\ncan send and get them for.\nBE HERE ABOUT THE 10TH\nLet the Free Press PrintYourSaleBiHs","height":"20472","width"